Modern Next.js E‑Commerce Website – Step‑by‑Step Project Plan

============================================================
GOALS
============================================================
- Build a production‑grade, modern e‑commerce web app using ONLY Next.js (frontend + backend).
- Showcase up‑to‑date design patterns, App Router usage, server actions, and modern React/TypeScript.
- Implement real e‑commerce flows: product catalog, product detail, cart, checkout (mocked payments), orders, and account area.
- Use high‑quality placeholder images from online sources for each page/section.


============================================================
TECH STACK & HIGH‑LEVEL ARCHITECTURE
============================================================
- Framework: Next.js (latest, App Router).
- Language: TypeScript.
- Styling: Tailwind CSS + CSS variables for theming.
- Components/UI: Reusable design system components (buttons, inputs, cards, modals, navigation).
- State Management:
  - Client: React state + context (for cart badge, UI state).
  - Server: Server Actions & cookies for cart/session where appropriate.
- Data Layer:
  - Start with in‑memory/JSON or filesystem “database” for products, categories, and users (no external DB to keep it 100% Next.js‑only).
  - Abstract data access through typed repositories/services so it’s easy to swap to a real DB later.
- Backend:
  - Next.js Route Handlers (`app/api/**`) for products, cart operations, authentication, and orders.
  - Server Actions for key mutations (add to cart, place order, update profile).
- Auth:
  - Simple email/password auth with hashed passwords stored in an in‑memory/JSON store + signed HTTP‑only cookies for sessions.
- Images:
  - Use `next/image` with remotePatterns configured.
  - Placeholder assets from Unsplash/Pexels/Freepik/etc. (collected via web search).


============================================================
PROJECT STRUCTURE (PLANNED)
============================================================
- `app/`
  - `layout.tsx` – Root layout, fonts, global providers, header/footer, theme.
  - `page.tsx` – Home / Landing page.
  - `(shop)/`
    - `products/`
      - `page.tsx` – Product listing (grid + filters/sorting).
      - `[slug]/page.tsx` – Product detail page.
    - `cart/page.tsx` – Cart page.
    - `checkout/page.tsx` – Checkout flow.
  - `(account)/`
    - `login/page.tsx`
    - `register/page.tsx`
    - `profile/page.tsx`
    - `orders/page.tsx`
  - `(content)/`
    - `about/page.tsx`
    - `contact/page.tsx`
  - `api/`
    - `products/route.ts`
    - `cart/route.ts`
    - `auth/login/route.ts`
    - `auth/register/route.ts`
    - `orders/route.ts`
- `lib/`
  - `products.ts` – product data + repo methods.
  - `auth.ts` – password hashing, session management helpers.
  - `cart.ts` – cart logic helpers.
  - `orders.ts` – order creation/retrieval.
- `components/`
  - `ui/` – generic UI kit (button, input, card, badge, modal, skeleton, etc.).
  - `layout/` – header, footer, main layout components.
  - `product/` – product card, product gallery, price tag, rating.
  - `cart/` – cart summary, cart line item, mini cart dropdown.
  - `forms/` – auth and checkout forms.
- `public/` – logos, basic assets (favicons, etc.).


============================================================
PHASE 1 – PROJECT INITIALIZATION
============================================================
1. Create Next.js App
   - Use `npx create-next-app@latest` with TypeScript, Tailwind, App Router enabled.
   - Clean out boilerplate content and set up base `layout.tsx` and `page.tsx`.
   - Configure global font (e.g., Inter, Geist, or Satoshi) via `next/font`.

2. Configure Tailwind & Global Styles
   - Set up Tailwind config with:
     - Custom color palette (light/dark).
     - Container widths, font sizes, spacing scale, border radius tokens.
   - Create global styles in `globals.css`:
     - Base typography.
     - Smooth scrolling, selection color, and base background/foreground colors.

3. Basic Layout & Navigation
   - Implement `Header` with:
     - Logo, main nav (Home, Shop, About, Contact).
     - Search input.
     - Cart icon with item count.
     - Account dropdown (Login/Register or Profile/Logout).
   - Implement `Footer` with:
     - Links (About, Contact, Privacy, Terms).
     - Social icons placeholders.
   - Wire `layout.tsx` to wrap all routes with header/footer.


============================================================
PHASE 2 – DATA MODEL & BACKEND FOUNDATIONS
============================================================
4. Define Core Types & Mock Data
   - Create TypeScript types:
     - `Product`, `Category`, `User`, `CartItem`, `Order`, `OrderStatus`.
   - Define static product catalog in `lib/products.ts`:
     - At least 12–16 products across 3–4 categories.
     - Include fields: name, slug, description, price, discount, images, badges (e.g., “New”, “Bestseller”), rating, stock, tags.
   - Add helper functions:
     - `getProducts`, `getProductBySlug`, `getFeaturedProducts`, `searchProducts`, `filterProducts`.

5. Implement Backend Utilities
   - `auth.ts`:
     - Hash/verify password helpers (e.g., using a simple algorithm or Node crypto).
     - Session cookie helpers (sign, verify, parse).
   - `cart.ts`:
     - Functions to manage cart stored in cookies or session (add, remove, update quantity, clear).
   - `orders.ts`:
     - Create order from cart, list orders for a user, get order details.

6. Create API Routes (Route Handlers)
   - `app/api/products/route.ts`:
     - `GET` list products with optional query params (search, category, sort, price range).
   - `app/api/cart/route.ts`:
     - `GET` get cart.
     - `POST` add/update/remove via action type payload.
   - `app/api/auth/login/route.ts`:
     - `POST` to authenticate user, set session cookie, return basic user info.
   - `app/api/auth/register/route.ts`:
     - `POST` to create user in memory store, hash password, set session cookie.
   - `app/api/orders/route.ts`:
     - `GET` list user’s orders.
     - `POST` create new order from cart, simulate payment success.


============================================================
PHASE 3 – CORE PAGES & FLOWS
============================================================
7. Home / Landing Page (`app/page.tsx`)
   - Hero section:
     - Large headline, subheading, CTA buttons (Shop Now / Learn More).
     - Background hero image from online placeholder (e.g., lifestyle, fashion, tech).
   - Featured collections:
     - Grid of 3–4 “collection” cards with background images.
   - Featured products carousel:
     - Use `getFeaturedProducts()` and display as horizontally scrollable cards.
   - Highlight sections:
     - Trust badges (Free Shipping, Secure Checkout, 24/7 Support).
     - Testimonials slider with avatar images from placeholders.

8. Product Listing Page (`app/(shop)/products/page.tsx`)
   - Layout:
     - Sidebar filters: Category, Price Range, Rating, Tags.
     - Top bar: Sort by (Price, Popularity, Newest), search input.
   - Product grid:
     - Responsive grid of `ProductCard` components with image, title, price, badges.
     - Skeleton loading states for smooth UX.
   - Interactivity:
     - Client‑side filters that call product API with query params.
     - Pagination or infinite scroll (choose one, likely pagination for clarity).

9. Product Detail Page (`app/(shop)/products/[slug]/page.tsx`)
   - Image gallery:
     - Main image + thumbnails (all placeholder images, per product).
   - Details:
     - Title, full description, price, discount, rating, stock indication.
   - Actions:
     - Quantity selector, Add to Cart button (server action or API call).
     - Wishlist button (client state only, for showcasing UI).
   - Related products section:
     - Use category/tags to show related items.

10. Cart Page (`app/(shop)/cart/page.tsx`)
    - Show cart items with:
      - Product image, name, selected variant (if any), price, quantity, subtotal.
    - Allow:
      - Update quantity, remove item, clear cart.
    - Summary:
      - Subtotal, estimated shipping, taxes, total.
    - CTA:
      - Proceed to Checkout button that leads to checkout page.

11. Checkout Page (`app/(shop)/checkout/page.tsx`)
    - Steps:
      - Shipping information form.
      - Payment method (mocked – no real gateway).
      - Order review.
    - Implement as:
      - Single page with stepper UI, or multi‑step form with client state.
    - On “Place Order”:
      - Call server action or `/api/orders` to create order, clear cart, redirect to order confirmation.


============================================================
PHASE 4 – AUTH & ACCOUNT AREA
============================================================
12. Auth Pages
    - `login/page.tsx`:
      - Email/password form, error handling, redirect if already logged in.
    - `register/page.tsx`:
      - Name, email, password, confirm password.
      - Validate strength and uniqueness (simple in‑memory check).
    - Use server actions and/or API calls to `auth` routes.
    - On success, set session cookie and redirect to account dashboard (profile or orders).

13. Account Pages
    - `profile/page.tsx`:
      - Show basic user info (name, email), allow editing profile (client‑side only or persisted in memory).
    - `orders/page.tsx`:
      - List previous orders with status, date, total.
      - Link to individual order details (optional nested route `[orderId]`).
    - Protect routes:
      - Middleware or server‑side checks to redirect unauthenticated users to login.


============================================================
PHASE 5 – CONTENT PAGES & BRANDING
============================================================
14. About Page
    - Brand story section with hero image.
    - Timeline or grid explaining mission, values, stats.
    - Team section with placeholder team member photos.

15. Contact Page
    - Contact form (name, email, message).
    - Static info: email, phone placeholder, address placeholder, map image placeholder.
    - Optional: simple API route to “submit” message (log to console or in‑memory).

16. Global Branding Enhancements
    - Define a consistent color system (primary, accent, neutrals).
    - Typography scale and spacing.
    - Button variants: primary, secondary, ghost, link.
    - Card styles, shadows, hover transitions, focus outlines.


============================================================
PHASE 6 – PLACEHOLDER IMAGES & MEDIA
============================================================
17. Gather Placeholder Images (via Web Search)
    - Search online sources (Unsplash, Pexels, Freepik, etc.) for:
      - Hero/banner images (high‑res, lifestyle/commerce‑oriented).
      - Product category images (e.g., fashion, electronics, home decor).
      - Individual product images (several per product).
      - Testimonials avatars and team member portraits.
      - Contact/office imagery.
    - Document image URLs and attributions (if needed) in a small markdown file.

18. Integrate With `next/image`
    - Configure `next.config.js` `images.remotePatterns` for external domains.
    - Replace placeholders in product data and section components.
    - Ensure responsive image behavior and proper `sizes` for performance.


============================================================
PHASE 7 – MODERN UX, ANIMATIONS & ADVANCED FEATURES
============================================================
19. Search & Filters
    - Implement global search bar in header hitting products API.
    - Debounced search input with results dropdown.
    - Deep‑linkable filter state (synced to URL query parameters).

20. Animations & Micro‑Interactions
    - Add subtle transitions:
      - Page transitions (fade/slide).
      - Hover effects on cards and buttons.
      - Cart icon “bump” animation on add‑to‑cart.
    - Use Framer Motion or CSS transitions (if kept strictly to Next.js stack, rely on CSS + React).

21. SEO & Performance
    - Use Next.js metadata for title, description, Open Graph tags.
    - Structured data (JSON‑LD) for product pages if appropriate.
    - Optimize LCP: priority hero image, minimal layout shift, prefetch key routes.
    - Lighthouse pass for performance, accessibility, best practices, SEO.

22. Accessibility
    - Ensure semantic HTML and ARIA where needed.
    - Keyboard navigable menus and dialogs.
    - Sufficient color contrast and focus states.


============================================================
PHASE 8 – TESTING, POLISH & DOCUMENTATION
============================================================
23. Testing Core Flows
    - Manually test:
      - Browsing products, filters, search.
      - Product detail and add to cart.
      - Cart updates and checkout flow.
      - Auth (register, login, logout).
      - Orders listing and order creation.
    - Fix any critical bugs or UX issues exposed.

24. Final Visual Polish
    - Fine‑tune spacing, typography, and breakpoints.
    - Ensure consistent use of components across pages.
    - Add 404 and 500 error pages with good UX and navigation back to shop.

25. Documentation
    - Create `README.md` with:
      - Tech stack overview.
      - Project structure explanation.
      - How to run the project (dev, build, start).
      - Notes on data layer and how to plug in a real database or payment provider.
      - Screenshots and links to key flows.


============================================================
NEXT ACTIONS
============================================================
- Initialize the Next.js project in this workspace following Phase 1.
- Then implement phases incrementally, committing at logical milestones (init, core pages, auth, advanced features, polish).
